<span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">The U.S. and Japan reached agreement Thursday on </span><span class="UnderlineChar">a long-stalled plan <span style="background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;">to move</span> troops off the island of Okinawa</span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">, a key part of the Obama administration's strategy to intensify its focus on Asia, and disperse American troops around the region. The new plan </span><span class="UnderlineChar">would move some 9,000 <span style="background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;">Marines off Okinawa</span></span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">, stationing about 5,000 of them on Guam and moving the remainder to Australia or Hawaii, U.S. defense officials said. </span><span class="UnderlineChar">There are now about 18,000 Marines in Okinawa</span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">. U.S. Defense Secretary Leon </span><span class="UnderlineChar">Panetta</span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;"> praised the agreement and </span><span class="UnderlineChar">said implementing the agreement <span style="background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;">would </span></span><span class="BoldUnderlineChar"><span style="background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;">improve the "vital alliance"</span></span><span class="UnderlineChar"><span style="background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;"> between the U.S. and Japan</span></span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">. </span><span class="UnderlineChar">"I look forward to deepening that friendship and strengthening our partnership as</span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">, together, </span><span class="UnderlineChar">we address security challenges in the region</span><span style="font-size: 6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;">," he said. Officials and analysts in Washington said </span><span class="Und